snippet.textDisplay:
Here are some electrical and power suggestions for your rig:

Wall mount your inverter. It needs to dissipate a lot of heat and should not be in an enclosed space.

You can add as many Rneogy RNG-100 panels as you have space on your roof (well, up to about 10). You can get a few Renorgy "branch connectors" ($12 each pair) to connect some of the panels in parallel.

The way you wired your 120V generator into your breaker panel will only energize breakers on one side since its a 240V panel. You can fix this by wiring the panel for 120V only with a jumper cable which will energize the breakers on the other side and give you power to all your outlets.

You will probably want to use your generator to run your air conditioner since it requires 660 watts and the compressor start up will create a current surge that m might temporarily exceed the power limits of your inverter.

Your lead acid batteries absolutely need to be outside of your living space since a lead acid battery can produce both hydrogen gas (flammable) and hydrogen sulfide gas which is colorless, very poisonous, flammable. Consider a battery box you can weld to the underside of the truck. Every one of the RVs you looked at had the batteries outside for a reason. Safety first!

snippet.textDisplay:
Guys, listen to your informed audience. Relocate those batteries! Follow code. You need to meet ventilation, fire barrier, arc proof wiring methods and circuit protection regulations. These are not hypothetical risks. All that has to happen is the charger either fails to recognize the battery is fully charged or the current limit setting is wrongly adjusted resulting in the solar panels overcharging your batteries and producing a lot of hydrogen that will collect inside the cabin, mix with the oxygen in the air, creating a very combustive, explosive atmosphere. Why does it collect? You got the HVAC going and have closed the door and windows to stay cool. Hydrogen is odorless, colorless and deadly. You've assembled a system, experienced some learnings, got it working but you have not proven it's safe operations under all conditions including probable malfunction or maladjustment. You need multiple safeguards independent of the occupant's actions.

You don't want to make the leap from YouTube to Fox News! I am not being critical just honest. I am an electrical engineer in the energy sector and I've investigated too many fatal incidents and several battery bank explosions! Most common cause casual design practices.
